title: Startrite Tilt Arbour Carriage bearing wheel/roller

description.text:
I have a Startrite tilt arbour, I think its a TA300PS or the TA1250, The rolling carriage has always been terrible and thus i took it off when i first got it but needs must...

I believe the TA1250 has bare bearings running on the carriage rail and thus I think my saw isnt a 1250, mine had been bodged and the nylon rollers had been replaced with a softer polymer without bearings... so there was little adjustment, the wheels were ovaled and the centre hole was 12mm instead of 8mm... it was terrible...

I trawled the internet for images/drawings and found some images of the actual parts, i think theres a company selling these but i didnt have the time to wait/im impatient and thus this is an approximation of the part and it seems to function nicely.

The design allows for a clip to hold the bearings in but its a friction fit anyway and since i didnt have any in im running without.

You should probably print these in a harder plastic than PLA but it seems to be working fine and since its only 24 grams for 4 units and 90 mins print time... PLA it is.

title: Remix conduits ventilos et centrage du bloc chauffant

description.text:
Remix des conduits de ventilation, centrage et isolement thermique de cette tête : https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2478810

ATTENTION cette pièce n'est PAS IMPRIMABLE sur une DiscoEasy ou une DiscoVery, mais a été imprimée avec une imprimante FORM2 en RESINE HAUTE TEMPERATURE (qui après post-processing résiste jusqu'à 300°C).

Cette pièce permet :

  • de rigidifier l'extrémité et de centrer le bloc de chauffe (voir image de centrage de la vis de serrage de l’élément chauffant), et de ce fait permet des prints plus précis (voir l'image Avant/Après des Benchy de 1,5 cm de hauteur, imprimés à 200um, 205°C, 60mm/sec), car la tête est immobilisée (en rotation et en XYZ)

  • de rapprocher et de concentrer les flux de refroidissement au plus près de la buse.

  • d'isoler thermiquement le bloc de chauffe (variation thermique de moins d'1°C au lieu de moins 10°C auparavant lors de la mise en route des 2x ventilos E3D à 100%.... avec ma carte Melzi... il parait que ce n'est pas le cas et que ça marche mieux avec les MKS )

(2017-11-06) La version v2 a été faite pour les utilisateurs ayant une buse montée au contact du bloc de chauffe. La première version a été conçue avec un jeu de 0.5 mm entre la buse et le bloc de chauffe. La v2 offre plus de sécurité de montage.

ENGLISH: ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Remix of the fan ducts, centering and thermal isolation of the heat block: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2478810

ATTENTION this piece is NOT PRINTABLE on a FDM printer, but was printed with a FORM2 printer with HIGH TEMPERATURE RESIN (which after post-processing resists up to 300 ° C).

This piece allows:

-to stiffen the nozzle position and to center the heating block (see cut picture of the heat block tightening screw), and thus allows more precise prints (see picture of the two benchies “before /after” –; both are 15 mm high, printed at 200um, 205 ° C, 60mm / sec), because the head is immobilized (in rotation and in XYZ)

  • to bring together and concentrate the cooling flows closer to the nozzle.
  • to thermally isolate the heating block (thermal variation of less than 1 ° C instead of minus 10 ° C before the start of the 2x E3D fans at 100% .... with my Melzi... it seems that this is not the case and that it works better with the MKS-Base…)
    (2017-11-06) Version v2 was made for users with a nozzle mounted in contact with the heating block. The first version was designed with a clearance of 0.5 mm between the nozzle and the heating block. The v2 offers more mounting security.

  • Demander un échantillon gratuit à Formlabs en Allemagne (voir demande d'échantillon sur leur site) en leur soumettant le fichier STL (ce service ne semble plus valide) https://formlabs.com/fr/materiels/materiaux-techniques/#high-temp-overview

  • Faire imprimer cette pièce par Sculpteo, par frittage laser (SLS) en poudre Nylon chargée en particules de verre. (Cette option a été testée avec succès par Moustache45 / Christian Nicot) : https://www.sculpteo.com/fr/materiaux/materiau-nylon/
    Voir le post de Christian Nicot sur DagomaNiack : https://www.facebook.com/groups/298369603868322/permalink/527864884252125/

Postprocessing

1) Après rincage IPA, les 4 trous taraudés M3 du centre demandent une attention très particulière:

  • perçage délicat en utilisant l'IPA comme lubrifiant (par petit va-et vient) A LA MAIN en augmentant la dimension des fôrets jusqu'à 2,8 mm de diamètre.
  • puis taraudage M3 toujours avec un peu d'IPA, A LA MAIN.

2) Toasté sur chaque face (dessus & dessous) à 60°C sous des UV @ 365 nm ET 405 nm, pour une durée de 40 minutes par face. Sinon, avec la FormCure (405 nm uniquement) 60°C, 60 min sur une face, et 60 min sur la face opposée.

ATTENTION ce matériau bien que très résistant thermiquement est cassant et peut se fracturer sous des sollicitations mécaniques trop fortes.

title: Shadowscape - Box Insert
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
Unsatisfied with the minimal amount of room the insert tray that came with the box allowed, and fueled by the desire to fit all the games materials in one package, I created this.

The goal was to make an insert tray with the following factors:

  • Ability to fit all components including expansions and miniatures.
  • Not damaging any of the previously mentioned pieces.
  • Minimising filament costs as much as possible.
  • Avoiding raising the lid of the box (otherwise, what's the point?)

The tray pieces are a little finicky and require packing a particular way, but using the files provided as well as the setup shown you can fit the game with all components, the Deeper Dungeon expansion, all miniatures, rule books, and both playmats WITHOUT raising the lid.

For further instructions on placement and usage, please read on.

Printer Brand:

FlashForge

Printer:

Creator Pro

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

25%

Notes:

Perimeter run increased to three times to help with strength.

You will need to print one of each file, excepting the tray bridges, which will you'll need four of. I used PETG, but really just because I've never used it before. ABS would have been fine, PLA may be too brittle though.

Sand all pieces well and remove any filament threads. Slot the tray bridges into each of the small wall gaps of the model trays to form the individual model chambers. Tolerances are in place for PLA (should snap in perhaps with a little finagling), other filament types may require filing to fit.

Done this way to allow sanding of the various pieces for a smoother finish (whereas solid walls would have made this much more annoying).

Tolerances for overall pieces in my print were made a little too tight, so I needed to file the back of the card holder to ease the fit. Otherwise, you should be good to go.

After the post-printing, we're left with the actual placement within the box. Once you've put this together and taken it apart a single time it's easy to remember.

Before everything else, remove the original insert tray. Give it to a loved one, or whatever it is you happen to do with things you don't want anymore.

  • Place the "Model_Tray_Lower" towards the side of the box. The fit should be tight, but not excruciatingly so, so make sure to have filed away any filament pooling from the bottoms and sides.
  • Once that's in place, insert the "Card_holder_b" so the long flat side forms a wall with the Model Tray.
  • "Model_Tray_Upper" is then rather logically placed on top of the lower model tray, pushing it all to one side.
  • Lastly, the "Component_Tray" fills the small gap left by placing the upper model tray.

The small divot at the bottom of each model chamber is to fit that character's token, to make it easier to organise them (and honestly just to give them some kind of use). To fit the tokens in, you'll need to place them beveled side down - they should kind of "click" in, with some pressure. They will jut out, this was to allow them to be removed in future. It has no effect on their ability to fit the models though.

Now for specifics...

The upper model tray is designed to fit the more "voluminous" character models; Siegred, Valkea, Fengray, and Venda, with the particularly large chamber reserved for Elatha (not sure what she did to deserve the extra large model >.<).

The lower tray fits the rest of them, with no particular placement of any kind required.

In order to maximise room I used the following component placements:

  • Cards dived between the two chambers, with one reaching the maximum height and the other one with space left.
  • Enemy tokens categorised by type are placed into tiny ziplock bags, purchased at Walmart. Two of the bags are placed on top of the smaller card pile, with the other one squeezing into the gap between the card chambers.
  • Wound tokens are bagged and left on the component tray, treasure and DL tokens are bagged and share the same model chamber as Elatha.
  • Finally, place the rulebook on top, as well as the folded up Deeper Dungeon rules and any playmats you may have printed on their as well.

Congratulations, you've just fit all of Shadowscape into a single box. If they make another expansion, I'll cry.

description.text:
Got some cheap filament from Microcenter, but the spindle is such a weird size, and the center hole is way too big, it barely fit in my spindle holder, and it made noise every time it moved because it rocked so much. I decided to make this thing so that I could get it running smoothly again. It takes 2 standard 22mm outside diameter skateboard bearings, though you could probably just run without them if you wanted and stick a rod through it. I've got a fascination with threads and making them really big and satisfying, so this thing has them. Also, since I am buying plastic at $15 a kg, I didn't feel too bad making this thing a plastic hog.

Currently working on a full spindle holder especially for this spindle size.

Printer:

Davinci 1.0 + E3D & Repitier

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2-.3 mm

Infill:

40%

Notes:

You need two skateboard bearings to make this work like its meant to. You can get them anywhere, but here's an easy amazon link https://www.amazon.com/eBoot-Pieces-Bearings-Hand-Multicolor/dp/B072KD8HKV/ref=sr_1_1_sspa?ie=UTF8&qid=1505563821&sr=8-1-spons&keywords=bearings&psc=1

The bearing hole diameter is 22.4mm. If your printer has a different kerf than that, you might want to figure something out. The outside Diameter for the part that goes inside the spindle hole is 53.89mm and tight, check with calipers if you're nervous. The threads however, should do pretty well with any reasonable kerf, they've got plenty of wiggle room.

Overhangs are like 50-60 degrees, and would not print well in ABS. Even with PLA with a cooling fan, I had some rough parts.

When done, just slip the clip on the Z-stage vertical plate, right below the microswitch.

This is an easy* clamp for a 4mm Bowden Tube.

I pulled on the Bowden Tube with as much force as I could...

Materials

RGB LED Strip:http://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/10-5M-SMD-5050-3528-RGB-300-600-LED-Strip-Adapter-IR-Remote-Waterproof-Kit-Xmas-/272710166331?var=&hash=item3f7ecae73b:m:mVUISZ0yyiZYo1kxUqGn0wQ
Whatever colour filament you want for the body/base (Mine was white but I recommend black)
Some translucent filament: https://rigid.ink/products/abs-1-75mm-3d-filament-0-03mm-tolerance-1kg-roll?variant=7692922305

Print Settings
Print in whatever orientation uses the least support. Bear in mind that inner ring top has a little bump on the top that will cause supports if printed face down.

I used 0.3mm resolution

Print everything except the translucent disk and the inner ring top at any density (20% is what I used)

The translucent disk should be at a low density, unless you want it to block more light. Mine was printed at 10%

The inner ring top should be a low density too, as it needs to flex slightly to hit the switch (Mine was 5%)

LED Soldering
Take the board out of your LED box, then desolder the power connector. Solder a momentary switch between one pin of the power connector and the board, making sure that it has enough wire to reach the inner ring bottom part.

Part assembly
There is a picture above that has the order of the parts

Superglue the translucent disk to the bottom plate, making sure it's aligned.

Put your LED strips between the 8 little pins surrounding the bottom plate (You can also add a bit of glue to stop them from moving)

Push inner ring bottom from the top of the base down.

Poke the momentary switch through the bottom of the center hole of inner ring bottom, then glue it in place, making sure that it still can click. (If you can't get the momentary switch through, just snap one of the little pins off, it's an issue I'm fixing for the next version)

Glue the power connector and infrared receiver through the gap in the base.

Make sure the wires aren't in the way, then put the base on top of the bottom plate, so that the pins go into the holes.

title: Box for eachine Lizard 95 (Version 2 with RunCam MicroSwift)

description.text:
This is my improved version of the Box for Lizard 95 (previous version see https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2472510 )
Most of all the Box was changed to fit for my modified Lizard 95 with a RunCam Micro Swift plus an ATX03 transmitter.
But it still fits to the stock model, rather more I added some options for this.
The empty space around the Skid is now used as additional spare parts box.
The closing "Bottom_Case_Closing.stl" is fixed with the part "Snap.stl" that must be mounted with an M3 screw at the bottom part "Case_bottom_Skid.stl".

For those who don't use my Landing Skid (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2472520) I have provided a smaller bottom case with some fixtures (Case_bottom_woSkid.stl).

If you want to create other parts around the Lizard I provided my simplified Lizard model as .stl and .obj.

Changing the stock camera to a RunCam Micro Swift is very easy:

  1. remove the cfk camera holder and reinstall it by rotation of 180° (so that the original camera would look backwards)
  2. remove the stock camera
  3. mount the printed part "ATX03_Antenna_holder" in the upper holes where the stock camera was fixed.
  4. mount the TX03 transmitter with some potection foam and a cable tie. The antenna position can be moved up and down as you like.
  5. drill a 2mm hole in the middle of a spare bolt and mount the Micro Cam with its frame here using an M2 srew and mount them on the cfk parts as shown on the pictures.

title: cubex e3d adapter for stock extruder

description.text:
You should use the built in limit switches, they're magnetic and function just like a mechanical switch. The only one I had to replace was the z-axis, but that avoids a lot of printed part mods.

When I first did my cubeX mod to make it open source, I used e3d-v6 (knock-offs, https://www.amazon.com/dp/B010MSTVZO) and found I could turn down the hex shank of the push-fit connector to be the same size as the stock hotend, and this extended it to be the correct length as well. I've built this https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2537620 to demonstrate.

I'm now using bowden (hopefully adapting https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1680034) with insight from http://www.prusaprinters.org/update-multimaterial-upgrade/ and http://www.prusaprinters.org/update-multi-material-upgrade-2/) for multimaterial printing

Make sure to upgrade the hotend with this https://www.amazon.com/dp/B01F82BMI8 or it'll be worthless for anything besides PLA.

Included a drawing of the e3d-v6 since it requires a model to post. Let me know if you want one, I can ship you one for shipping cost ($7).

title: ANET A8 Spiral vase linear bushing

description.text:
Yet another linear bushing ?

Yes but this one is a bit special as, if you follow the process, it will print in "spiral vase" which means:

  • it will be very accurate !... The Spiral Vase setting of Slic3r will raise Z continuously avoiding a layer-change point which would cause a visible seam. The accuracy is given by parametrization of the diameters. It will fit direct from the printer once parametrized to your printer.
  • A chamfer is included at both extremities on the inner and outer diameters. (no need to trim anything)
  • it can be made springy
  • it is self centering
  • it is very light (around 1g each which means you win 50 g on the Y carriage)
  • it has low friction and slides on the whole surface of the rods
  • everything is customizable and MUST be customized (see below). As they cost nothing (around 2 cents each) you can play with them, print 4 or 5 prototypes to get the perfect fit. To open the customizer click on the button "open in customizer" just at the bottom right of the picture...

Only drawback, it must be installed inside a standard bushing just because it has to be set inside a cylindrical housing to keep a regular shape.

They are installed on my Y axis and so far they do a great job!

see it here: https://youtu.be/BviIuek-uW4

you collect it, like it, made it ? please click on the like button and should you be on a good day, please consider leaving a $1 tip this would help for my R&D department ;-)

Printer:

ANET A8

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2 with a 0.4 nozzle

Infill:

none - spiral vase

Notes:

I printed in PLA. I don't use any lubricant.

This thing must be sliced with Slic3r using the spiral mode. See the 3rd picture. Do not forget to remove the bottom (with 0 layer).

EDIT : Cura slicer has also a spiralize mode. The settings are included in the last picture ...

Obviously, you shall print them one by one to get the spiral mode working...
Duration of print is only 5 minutes for one bushing.

Again, please read the next paragraph, the trimming must be done in customizer or (faster) directly with Openscad which is freeware.

let's customize it ...

It is mandatory to trim this model under the customizer or directly with openscad.

You must trim at least the following parameters :

// the outer diameter in mm
outerD=15.0;
Print some samples and adjust outerD first without modifying anything else. Once you get a bearing that fits exactly inside the bushing, you can play with the second parameter (inside diameter)

// inner diameter in mm
innerD=8.0;
The inner diameter can be set here. For a standard LM8UU, just leave this value to 8 mm

// this is used to trim the inner diameter (mm)
filament_margin = 0.92;
The spiral vase prints one perimeter just inside the perimeter of the rod... This "filament margin" is here to offset the inner diameter (increase this value to increase the size of the hole). On my printer with a noozle of 0.4 mm and a layer of 0.2, the filament width is around 0.45mm which means 0.90 on the diameter.
Basically start with 0.90 and play with this value to get the bushing nearly fully free on the rod (see the video to feel how accurate you have to be...)

You may as well play with the other parameters :

// height in mm
H=23.8; //23.8;
This is the height of the bushing. For a 24 mm, I left 0.2 mm free...

// number of spikes
N = 10;
If you want so, you can play with this to reduce or increase the number of blades or spikes.
10 seems to be the maximal value.

// spike angle
spike_angle = 30;
The blades are not perpendicular to the perimeter they are oriented with an angle. The bigger the angle, the more springy bushing you get. If you do not want any springy effect, set this value to 0.

// twist of blades in deg
blade_twist = 30;
On standard bushing (IGUS like) the spikes are fully radial which means that the friction is applied always on the same part of the rods. To get an even wear of the rods, you can twist the spikes pattern so that along the lenght of the bushing every part of the rods will be in contact of the printed bushing. Set it to 0 if you do not want this !

description.text:
2017-12-12 Update: A new snap on filament guide is now available: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2710135

This is a 608 bearing based spool holder that snaps securely on to popular aluminum extrusions used by a variety of 3D printers. Parts for 2020, 2040 and 3030 extrusions have been included.

Why I'm a big fan of this design (inspired by remix source):

  • Simply put a spool on or lift it off. No rods, screws, nuts, etc.
  • Easy to snap on, off or re-position as needed
  • Bearing based for smooth filament feeding
  • Ideal for direct drive extruders like the Titan Aero as the filament is fed from above

I deliberately avoided adding notches to fit into the extrusion channels to avoid compatibility issues between v-slot and t-slot. This design also won't interfere with belts or cables in the channels.

The complete kit requires:
4 x 608 Bearings (AliExpress, Ebay, Amazon) or take the bearings out of fidget spinners
2 x Spool Brackets for your extrusion dimensions
2 x Side pieces

I designed these parts with tight tolerances:

  • 0.0mm on the bearing so it should be held securely in place with only finger pressure to mount it.
  • 0.1mm on the extrusion dimensions for a tight snap fit and minimal wobble.

Although it should be a good fit, If you feel like it's a little loose:

  • Use glue.
  • User Ruwaa has a make listed here where they used nuts and bolts (great idea!): http://www.thingiverse.com/make:406961

It was designed in OnShape so anyone can modify/remix the parts or export them to another format from here:
https://cad.onshape.com/documents/29eb71db69e1bb7318d53beb/w/42585bfe3de101322142941e/e/df372655fda7ed3c82d11cde

This is a remix of Spudinator's Crusader GT2 bumper and quad TC-R motor and arm protector V1 by nickpgre. (big thanks to both of you). Remix is to provide better protection for motors and less chances of sand gravel getting in the motors.

Nice thing about the TC-R motor/arm protector is that you can attach with a little strip of 2 sided tape between the motor screws on the bottom of the arm, then just push the openings in the protector over the motor screws. This works for the remixed bumper as well. An added side benefit is that the TPU on the ends of the arms also seems to dampen vibration.

Printed with Inland eFelx (TPU) fliament, 230 on printhead, 70 bed temp. Disabled retraction at first but eventually turned it back on to reduce stringing, 1.0 mm distance, 15 mm/s speed.

Also slowed everything way down, 15mm/s bottom/top, 20mm/s inner/outer shell, 25mm/s infill, 50 mm/s travel, because this is the default extruder which does not do well with flexible filament. Make sure you are leveled accurately so the first layer goes down right. I had to increase the first layer to 150% width to get good results.

description.text:
The Nike Smoke was a sounding rocket used by NASA in the 1960's for atmospheric research.

This model is 21.5" tall and the fin span is slightly less than 6". The tallest part is the nose cone at about 8.5".

The inside diameter is 1.6", so standard centering rings could be used to make this a flyable model rocket.

The shell is 1mm thick allowing for two extrusions of .5mm. The fin section and mid section connect with a twist-lock bayonet fitting, as do the nose cone and nose cone base. The nose cone base slip-fits into the mid section.

I have not tried launching one of these myself, and I don't know how well the common 3D printing materials like PLA will hold up to the heat of a rocket engine ejection charge, so proceed at your own risk. Double-perimeter fins can add weight to the rear of the rocket, so pay attention to the CG/CP relationship to ensure stability.

Printer Brand:

SeeMeCNC

Printer:

ORION Delta 3D Printer

Resolution:

.2mm layers

Infill:

None

Notes:

The example shown is printed in white MARS PLA.

See the uploaded Slic3r settings.zip file.
Copy the Slic3r settings files into the filament/print/printer folders at
C:Users > yourID > AppData > Roaming > Slic3r

The perimeter, infill, and retraction settings are key to getting a nice looking exterior while still being sturdy. The printing of the fin section involves so many retractions that it required setting the "extra length on restart" to a positive value to re-prime the hot-end and prevent under-extrusion in some areas.

Print each section in the orientation shown in the 2nd photo to eliminate need for supports. The designed-in supports for the fin section should break off easily.

The mid section has an internal lug near the nose for attaching a shock cord/parachute if you decide to use this as a flying model rocket.

If the bayonet fittings are too tight, don't force them as this can cause the plastic to friction-weld together and you might not get them apart again. Instead, use some sandpaper to sand the grooves a bit, and use a candle to rub some paraffin onto them as lubricant.

It should be possible to make a motor mount using two 1.6" centering rings, a motor tube, a thrust ring, and a motor retainer. The centering rings would need to have four notches filed into them so the mount can be inserted into the fin section past the bayonet bumps. There is a lip inside the very bottom of the fin section to retain the motor mount.
When the mid section is attached to the fin section, the motor mount will be held in place without glue. This would allow you to swap in different size motor mounts.

The nose cone base is sized so that it will probably require some sanding to slip inside the mid-section. It needs to be a snug fit to keep the nose cone from wobbling.

You could print the fin section with a single perimeter to get the best exterior appearance and minimize the amount of sanding and filling needed. But the fins would be somewhat frail, and might not stand up to the rigors of launch and recovery. Depending upon the material used, the mid section might experience some melting or warping from the heat of an ejection charge.

Used Gurgelx controller holders to integrate neodymium magnets and attach it to a piece of 1/2" PVC to make it more affordable. Now you can pop the controller out and in via the magnets.

Print 2 controller bases and 1 of each controller (right and left). Cost me about $25 for all 4 pieces (may be less if you have a hook up).

Buy about 4' of 1/2" Schedule 40 PVC pipe from the hardware store. (~$2)
https://www.lowes.com/pd/Charlotte-Pipe-1-2-in-x-5-ft-600-Schedule-40-PVC-Pipe/3133081

Get 2 elbows and 2 caps (~$1.50)

Buy these pipe clamps (the controller bases are made to work specifically with these clamps. (make sure it's the #0 ones - $2.65)
http://www.homedepot.com/p/0-ACC-Conduit-and-Pipe-Hangers-5-Pack-26780/100130865

I've also found that a 1/4" nut for each clamp helps bolt it on really tight and sturdy.

These magnets work great ~$8.50 (you can also skip the magnets and just glue the pieces together and slip the controllers in and out of the holders - similar to Gurgelx' version)
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01I1ZB2SE/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o00_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

Total Cost - about $40 (unless you can 3d print yourself, then it's way cheaper)

Optional: screw an eye hook into the PVC elbow and use a single point harness (~$5 on ebay)

description.text:
Project I designed around Adafruit's CircuitPlayground Express : A light source that will will turn on/off based on what side it's on (bottom/top), change intensity if you tilt it front/back, and change color if you tilt it left/right.
Video of it in action:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JtTI1Bfv6ug

You'll need to print one of each part: I designed a 'case' for the CPE that fits into the light, then a ring snap-fits it into place. Note the case is a remix of parts from Adafruit's "Circuit Playground Neopixel YoYo", Thing #1766385
I modeled the light in Autodesk Maya.

Things you will need:

  • The Circuit Playground Express: https://www.adafruit.com/product/3333
  • A Micro-USB cable, capable of carying data (not just charge).
  • A 3D printer capable of printing something roughtly 8" square by 6" tall.
  • Your CPE flashed to run CircuitPython, and loaded with the provided Python module. I have a tutorial here covering how to do this: http://www.akeric.com/blog/?p=4294
  • This CircuitPython project also requires the use of the Adafruit neopixel and adafruit_lis3dh bundles (Python moudles), also explained in the tutorial.

Notes:

description.text:
*Update - Added Tray_Short_v5 file which is 5mm taller. This one fits the short bins tighter.

Magnetic Storage Tray for Gaming Miniatures

I designed these trays for my own personal storage solution for Descent 2nd edition miniatures. There is a short version and a tall version. They require .25" x .125" magnets in the trays, and I used .25" x .0625" magnets in the bottom of the miniatures. After putting magnets in the tray, I glued .125" cork to the bottom of the tray. I used a router/router table to route a slot in the bottom of the miniature for the magnet to fit up inside. I used 5 minute epoxy to seal the magnet to the bottom of the miniature. The tray side-supports serve two purposes. First, they act as a handle to remove the tray from the bin. Second, they are the exact height of the inside of the bin with the lid on. If the bin gets flipped upside down, the tray stays where it's supposed to and doesn't slide and push the tops of the miniatures into the lid. The tray has 63 total magnet holes, although not all are needed if you are using larger base miniatures.

The tray is broken up into 4 pieces as I only have a 200mm x 200mm print bed. The base size of the single part is 125mm x 160mm. The assembled base is 250mm x 320mm. You will need to print 4 parts to make 1 tray (2 normal, 2 mirrored). They can then be glued or bolted together. I bolted mine together with (6) m3x16 bolts, (6) m3 nuts, and (12) m3 washers. There are also filament slot guides on 2 sides of all tray parts. You may need to use a 1.75mm to 1.9mm drill bit to clean and open them up a little. Then use small pieces of 1.75mm filament to give extra support between the tray pieces. This also helps in keeping the pieces aligned while gluing/bolting together and while gluing the cork to the bottom. Links for the plastic bins and magnets are below.

The cost of the magnets I needed for 200+ miniatures (need 2 magnets minimum for each miniature - 1 for tray, 1 for miniature) ended up being more than I expected. I have spent so much $ buying all the parts of the actual game that it was worth it to me to set up a good storage/transport system. For most people, this design will not be cost effective. I thought I would upload this in case someone could use it.

It wasn't until I wrote this up and added the links that I realized the plastic bins are only available at retail Walmart stores. They are not available for online purchase.

description.text:
Warning First of all this is a huge work in progress and if you print this you WILL have to use sandpaper to smooth out the sides where the semi circle is out the bottom and also the cable may need some sanding to look right!

Tesla has started putting these new urban superchargers so that people can charge even if they don't have a home charger instead of using the regular superchargers. This is not a scale model or even a perfect replica, I just think it looks cool on my shelf next to my regular supercharger that I printed. FDM printers do leave the model looking a little funny but its passable and from far away it look great.

Also I am working on a stand to hold it but it does stand up on its own but not that well
IMAGES COMING SOON

What to Print

2x sides (In white if you are going for the real look)
1x The Middle (Gray for the real look)
2x Tesla Logos (In Red)
1x Cable (In Black) (WITH SUPPORTS)

How to get the Parts Ready For Assembly

1) Sand the sides especially at the bottom where the semi-circle is to make it smooth
2) Sand the cable
3) Sand any other parts you so wish to get the look you are going for

This will be improved as I get better at modeling I just did basic shapes and didn't have time or the want to make them line up because I knew it would be easier just to sand it

Assembly

1) Glue the tesla logo in the holes on the sides (it might not fit I would just like up the bottom and use a tooth pick to put glue around the sides of the logo as you hold it down)

2) Get the cable and glue it in place at any points you wish

3) Glue the sides to the middle lining it up at the top to leave space at the bottom like it is in the real thing

4) Let it dry!

title: Star Trek - Deep Space Nine Danube Class Runabout 1/70 scale (13 inches / 33 cm)

description.text:
After printing the original model of the Runabout i wanted te build a bigger version. One that could have LED lights installed to make the model come to life.

The model is 1/70 scale and so the total length of the model is 33 cm (13 inches). You will have to follow the printing instructions i have written and also it would help to view the build log i posted on Youtube of this Runabout build.

Link to the build log: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLtTCQ0DBBLzF56kbQ9n5aPAkfsldfcZEN

If there are any questions, don't hesitate to ask them in the comments, as this is a rather complex build.

Also included is a pdf with custom made decals for this model. Print them out on decal paper or transparant sticker material.

Update October 15th
Today uploaded the impuls wings again, because EOD found out that the old files were not in scale. My first export in trying to get all files matching failed so needed to do the impuls wings again.
Also this is only one impuls wing, to get the other mirror it in your slicing software.

Printer:

Anet A8

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.1

Infill:

10%

Notes:

Okay here we go with the print instructions:

Most of the parts don't need supports, but there are a few that need support for the best results.

The main body of the ship is split into 4 parts, these are the Rio_Grande lower back, lower front, upper back and upper front files.
My recommendation for these 4 parts is to print them with a wall thickness of 3 mm and a top thickness of 3mm, the bottom layer you can make as thin as 0.3mm (3 layers at 0.1mm layer heights) This is so that you can easily cut parts out of the bottom so hollow out the main body for installation of the electronics. Also print with a low infill, max 10% (You will need to remove parts of the infill. See video logs for details on this.

Then the nacelles:
The body is split in 2 peaces the top and bottom. I printed the tops in the orientation of the file (right side up) and used supports for the inside, this way the top details are the best.
The bottom part i rotated 180 degrees, so that this is printed the same as the top part.

The Impuls wings are split into 3 parts, the front, the starboard body and the insert.
As the starboard name suggests this is only one of the impuls wings, you will need to mirror these 3 parts to create the port side of the impuls wings. These 3 parts don't need supports. As you print the front part flat on the printbed.

As for the wings, these need supports!
I printed the wings in the upright orientation, so that the build layers are the same as on the main body of the model. This however will need a large amount of support because of this. So decide for yourself. Also make sure to use at least a wall thickness of 2mm, otherwise you could end up with holes in the wings.

The chiller grills and Bussard collector caps are to be printed in a translucent material. I used translucent red and blue PETG (main model is PLA) The bussard you can stand up its end, and then you do not need supports. I would suggest a layer height of 0.05 for the caps, so that the round top on the front is the best possible.

Gold bands for Nacelles:
If you have a sample pack of gold or yellow PLA, i would suggest to use that for these bands. These print as a long strip and what i did was i printed this, and while it was still at temperature (60 degrees celsius) i would manually bend the part around the nacelle. See video log and photo for details on the final finish.

Additional i have window inserts for all the windows. If you do not want to paint the windows black because of fear that you can't get the good finish, then you can use black PLA to print the window inserts at a 0.3mm hight (would use 0.1 layers). The front windows need to be bent into shape like the gold bands, see videolog.

Also additional i have included a lightblock strip, this could be printed in black PLA to insert between the Impuls wings and the outer wings, so that the lights you install in the impuls engines don't spill out between the engines and outer wings. (see video log) and a Warpcore LED holder, this is a small round peace that can hold a 5mm LED and make gluing that peace in place a little easier.

I printed the parts in ABS, They fit, but they are snug.
I sanded the outside of the trays, just enough to get the grooves off
I also sanded the inside of the box until the trays fit and move in and out freely.

I did not sand the spacer, which arguably, should be printed in, but it does not come out so a tight fit is fine.

I glued the trim ring on to the lid with Plastruct Bondene. This was an early project, before I had learned that the way to work with Bondene is with a syringe with a 25 ga. transfer needle.

The original version of this design is brilliant. However, on my old printer, I couldn't get it to print without warping (in ABS). So I re-made it from scratch using the original as a guide. The jaw channels are very similar, but slightly deeper, and the width of the jaws (amount of jaw that is flat against the print bed) has been increased to help adhesion. The outside of the jaws has been simplified to a triangular design with less curves, simply because it was easier to model.

The guide channel (part that slides) has been modified to lock more. Original design had shallower guide channel which didn't manifest very well when printed on my printer.

I've attached a Sketchup file (version 7) for anyone interested in tweaking it some more.
